3) Universal scaling laws describe the behavior of the curves
The quantities defining the optimal generalization—εopt and λopt—exhibit a simple power-law dependence
on the dataset size. This same scaling can be used to normalize the curves, causing the large-λ region
to collapse across different dataset sizes.
2) Dynamical equivalent of the problem passes near static solution
An equivalent formulation can be obtained by treating λ as the norm of the perceptron and fixing the loss
parameter to 1. Training a free-norm perceptron under this setup allows comparison between the
generalization error ε(λ) obtained from the dynamics and the one from the static analysis. Qualitatively,

tspan.tspan: the two curves exhibit the same behavior

text.tspan: 1) Cross-entropy interpolates between classical learning rules
For the fixed-norm, fully trained perceptron, the generalization error—defined as the expected fraction of
misclassified examples on new data—can be computed analytically as a function of λ. As λ increases,
the perceptron first behaves like Hebb’s rule, then converges to the Bayes-optimal solution, and
eventually overfits by approaching the maximum-stability rule.

TLDR
For both perceptrons and deep architectures, the model norm serves as a powerful lens to study
learning behavior, revealing universal patterns across different regimes.
Teacher-Student Perceptron Setup
• w* ∈ ℝⁿ: teacher weights, w ∈ ℝⁿ: student weights
• Stabilities
• Student infers w* from P=αN labeled examples
• Loss: cross-entropy
• Norm constraint: ‖w‖² can be fixed (‖w‖² = N) or free
• Goal: minimize loss to align w with w*
Possible implications
Analogies in scaling laws suggest an implicit bias in deep networks throughout the whole learning
procedure, where early training favors low-complexity solutions and overfitting emerges as the
norm grows.
